Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Download: Workers Spend Thousands on 'BYOD'
Headlines.Author: Michael Hickins
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Download: Workers Spend Thousands on 'BYOD'

PARAGRAPH.#text: Employees spend thousands on their own devices. Companies that don't allow employees to pick their own mobile devices seem like they're becoming the exception rather than the rule -- and no wonder. CIO Journal has an exclusive look at a report from Forrester Research showing just how much of their own money employees are willing to spend on devices they use for business: chief executives and presidents spend the most, averaging over $3,000 per year, but even average workers spend more than $1,200. They're betting their work performance will improve enough that raises will more than pay for what they pony up on their own. And CIOs won't have to foot that bill either.

Headlines.Author: Tess Stynes
Headlines.Headline: S&P Upgrades Unisys On Improved Results, Liquidity Levels

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Standard & Poor's Ratings Services upgraded its junk-level grade on Unisys Corp.

a notch on what analyst Martha Toll-Reed called the information-technology provider's improved operating performance of late and "adequate liquidity" levels. The B+ rating, four steps from investment-grade territory, reflects S&P's view that Unisys' "moderate leverage for the rating" and consistent annual free cash flow provide enough cushion amid weakening revenue and "a lack of operating performance predictability." However, a reversal of the upgrade could occur if annual operating cash flow and debt ratios decline for at least two straight quarters.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: S&P Upgrades Unisys On Improved Results, Liquidity Levels

Headlines.Author: John Kell
Headlines.Headline: Moody's Gives 2-Notch Boost To Unisys On Improved Performance

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Moody's Investors Service lifted its junk-level rating on Unisys Corp.

by two notches, citing the information-technology company's improved operating performance over the last year. The ratings agency touted the company's solid free cash flow, reduced balance sheet debt, improved liquidity profile and credit metrics, which it said should continue in the near term. After years of incurring significant restructuring charges, Unisys has positioned itself to generate consistent levels of profits and cash flow, said Moody's.

Headlines.Headline: BEFORE THE BELL:US Stock Futures Lower Ahead Of Data

PARAGRAPH.#text: (updates prices, details on Qwest Communications and International Paper) By Barbara Kollmeyer U.S. stock futures fell on Wednesday as markets absorbed another busy day of earnings, along with a full schedule of economic data, including durable-goods orders and new-home sales. S&P 500 futures were down 5.6 points to 1,054.80 and Nasdaq 100 futures were down 4.5 points at 1,715.25. Futures on the Dow Jones Industrial Average slipped 50 points to 9,784. U.S. stocks ended mostly lower Tuesday after economic reports offered positive news on the housing front, but reduced confidence among consumers.
